<dl id="n10074c"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n10" href="#n10074c">N10 (VI.B.16)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n10all.htm#n10074c"> 74(c)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> fernsprecher <small>Blue</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n10074c"> <li>FW unlocated</li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">Reis se mit imm&eacute;diatement &agrave; l&apos;oeuvre, construisit tant bien que mal, un appareil rudimentaire, d&apos;apr&egrave;s la description qu&apos;en avait donn&eacute;e Bourseul, et le nomma: <i>T&eacute;l&eacute;phone</i>, qui vient de deux mots grecs: <i>t&ecirc;l&ecirc;</i>, loin; <i>ph&ocirc;n&ecirc;</i>, voix; les Allemands le nomment <mark><i>Fernsprecher</i></mark>, ce qui veut dire <i>parler au loin</i>, absolument la m&ecirc;me chose. <font color="green">[Reis immediately set to work and built, after a fashion, a rudimentary device following the description Boursel had given. He called it the Telephone, which comes from two Greek words, tele, far and phone, voice. The Germans called it <i>Fernsprecher</i>, which means talking at a distance, which is absolutely the same thing.]</font> <small> Eug&egrave;ne Gallois, <a name="EGLP" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#EGLP"><cite title="source">La Poste</cite></a> (1894) 368</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: <cite>FW</cite> 536.02, BL-484b-362 JJA 59:090 entered later (at III:3B.12), probably does not derive from this notebook. </mm> </dd></dl>
